ions in earthenware, stoneware, porcelain, glaze, and surface decoration from Africa, Asia, Europe, the Middle East, and the Americas. Essays describe the core materials and practice of ceramics, followed by consideration of its production, consumption, and use. Throughout, the focus is on the power of materials and the role conservation plays in the afterlife of a ceramic object.An accessible introduction to an ancient practice, Ceramic Art offers new ways of thinking about the broader forces that have shaped the traditions of the medium.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPotteryxConservation and restoration. 7aART / Ceramics.2bisacsh1 aFowler, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraves, Margaret S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmquist Pachas, Ulla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmquist, Ulla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnappett, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Sequoia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMiller, Sequoia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOdundo, Magdalene, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOdundo, Magdalene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParry, Vicki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoh, Soon Kai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeinryb, Ittai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYou, Yao-Fen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2023z9783111318103oZDB-23-DPK08iTi